LAGOS â€“ The Lagos State Police Command has arraigned a 24-year-old man, Opeyemi Sikiru, before a Lagos State Magistrate Court for allegedly assaulting a police officer and stealing a phone worth N13,000. Sikiru, a tiller who resides at Ijeh Police Barracks, is standing trial on a two-count charge of stealing and assault preferred against him by the police. He was granted bail in the sum of N100,000 by Magistrate, Mrs. T.B. Are. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network At the resumed hearing of the matter, the prosecutor, Inspector Abbass Abayomi, told the court that the defendant committed the offence on January 4, 2020. He said the incident occurred at about 12:25 p.m. at Line A, Block 1, at a barber shop at Ijeh Police Barracks, Lagos. Abayomi alleged that the defendant stole a Tecno model F1, cell phone valued at N13,000, property of one Ramat Ismaila. The prosecutor also accused the defendant of assaulting a police officer, Umaru Mohammed, by head butting him, causing him bodily injury. According to the prosecutor, the offence committed is punishable under Section 287 and 173 of the Criminal Law of Lagos State 2015. However, the defendant pleaded not guilty to the charge against him. Magistrate Are, granted him bail in the sum of N100,000, with two sureties in like sum. She said that the sureties must be gainfully employed and resident in Lagos. The Magistrate ordered that the sureties must show evidence of tax payment to the Lagos State government and have their addresses verified. She adjourned the case till January 21, 2020, for mention.